    <a href="/reading/operating-systems/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to Operating Systems</a>

    <h1>Protection and Security</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Wikipedia &middot; <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_security"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Computer security</a> &middot; CC BY-SA 4.0</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none"><strong>Protection</strong> controls which processes can access which resources. <strong>Security</strong> defends the system against external threats. The access control matrix is the theoretical foundation. Authentication, encryption, and auditing are the practical tools.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>Access control</h3>
    <p>The OS must answer: can subject S perform operation O on object X? The <strong>access control matrix</strong> maps every (subject, object) pair to a set of allowed operations. In practice, the matrix is sparse, so it is stored as either access control lists (columns) or capability lists (rows).</p>

    <!-- SVG: Access control matrix (subjects x objects) -->
